name: Justin E. Herdman
office__address__courthouse: Office of the United States Attorney
articles__title: Federal Officials Seek To Answer Concerns About Operation Legend
articles__summary: Justin Herdman, U.S. Attorney for the Northern District of Ohio, describes Operation Legend as a typical federal partnership.

name: David DeVillers
articles__title: New U.S. attorney David DeVillers a familiar face as prosecutor in central Ohio
articles__summary: David DeVillers has had stints overseas, helping to prosecute Saddam Hussein and cut down on corruption in a number of other countries. But he has spent much of his legal career in central Ohio, cracking down on gang, drug, gun and other criminal activities. He’ll continue that work as the new U.S. attorney for the Southern District of Ohio.

name: Carter M. Stewart
articles__title: Investigation Finds Most Complaints Against Columbus Police During Protests 'Not Sustained'
articles__summary: Review is being led by John Glenn College of Public Affairs dean Trevor Brown and former U.S. Attorney Carter M. Stewart, who will hire a team of researchers and community members to interview both officers and protesters.

name: Dave Yost
articles__title: Editorial: For Ohio attorney general: Dave Yost is the better choice
articles__summary: The Columbus Dispatch endorses Dave Yost

name: Joseph T. Deters
articles__title: Race Could Be Key Issue In Deters-Rucker Fight For Prosecutor's Office
articles__summary: After former municipal judge Fanon Rucker won the Democratic primary for Hamilton County Prosecutor, all eyes moved to Republican Joe Deters, the 22-year incumbent he will face in November.

name: Michael O’Malley
articles__title: No Democrat or Republican to challenge Cuyahoga County Prosecutor Michael O’Malley in 2020
articles__summary: Cuyahoga County Prosecutor Michael O’Malley appears to be headed toward a second term in office.

name: Ron O’Brien
articles__title: Tyack says his stroke not an issue in race against O'Brien for Franklin County prosecutor
articles__summary: Former Appeals Court Judge Gary Tyack said he hopes to be released from a rehabilitation center Friday, three weeks after suffering what his campaign called a "mild stroke," and is committed to resuming his campaign against incumbent Franklin County Prosecutor Ron O'Brien.
